Overall Question:

How is general health related to weight and exercise?

It is commonly thought that an individual in good health exercises frequently and has a lower weight. However, this is not always the case. It is important to compare general health with weight and exercise in order to determine if there is a correlation between the two and if any outliers exist.

This question is important because it may give insight on best practices for optimal health (at least in terms of weight and exercise). That is to say, if the data gives a solid answer to this question, then light is shed on the best way to become more healthy.

The insight on best practices for optimal health is an important insight because this information can be distributed to the general public, who (hopefully), will use it to improve their own health. ## Plot to answer the Question

#gen health vs. exercise
d <- ggplot(cdc,aes(genhlth));
d+geom_bar(aes(y=..prop..,group=1,fill=..x..))+facet_wrap(~exerany)+scale_fill_gradient(low="green",high="red")+
  labs(x = "Health",y="Proportion",title = "Relationship Between Exercise and General Health") #this looks at health and exercise

Conclusion

We focus on the relationship between exercise and the general health, and how the exercise affects our health. And most people often thought the more exercise, the healthier they are, but why this holds?

In order to provide a solid answer to this main question, we plot the bar diagram to visualize their relationship and the general health distribution. In this bar chart, it shows that when people do exercise more, the proportion of their excellent health quality is high, and majority persons lie on very good health. Only a few people are in poor health. However, comparing left side which fewer exercise with right side, the proportion indicates that the people in excellent health are less than right, and the majority people are in good health. The number of persons who are in poor health rises a lot.

Therefore, the regular exercise not only helps us to keep good health, but improve our life quality. And the best way to keep health is to do more exercise.

Summary of Who did What

Lauren

The data has been divided into two groups: 1 indicates that the individuals have exercised in the past month and 0 indicates otherwise. Additionally, a linear fit has been assigned to males (m) and females (f) comparing individuals actual weight versus desired weight. I have also included a black line; this line indicates an individual whose desired weight is his actual weight. With this understanding of the plot, we can make some interesting observations. In both the exercise and non-exercise groups, the linear fit for males is closest to the control line. This gives the impression that males have less of a difference between their desired and actual weight, compared to females. Additionally, it appears the linear fit for males is closer to the control line for the non-excerise group. This implies that men who have exercised in the past month have a larger desire to change their weight.

Ryan

My individual exploration sought to explore two concepts in health. The first concept was the relationship between general health and exercise, and the second (somewhat more abstract) sought to explore the relationship between a person’s current weight, and their desired weight loss. The first plot I created aimed to visualize the distribution of health for the set of people who DO exercise, and for the set of people who DO NOT exercise at all. The findings from this exploration fit my hypothesis exactly! The majority of exercisers report having “very good” health, while the majority of non-exercisers report only having “good” health. The way the plot is set up, higher general health is toward represented to the left, while lower general health is represented toward the right. The general heatlth reports from the set of people who do exercise is quite obviously shifted left (toward health) when compared to the health reports from the set of people who do not exercise. This has direct and obvious relation to the team’s question.

The exploration of the data presented in the second plot was motivated mainly by a desire to observe the extent to which people wish their weight was different, and how this changes based on their current weight. One would expect to see a linear increase in desired weight loss as weight increases (I speculate this because “optimal weight” is likley a constant which is set by health/beauty standards in a society, a person’s family/upbringing, and many other factors). The plot shows that in general, this is true. Most of the heavier people want to lose more weight than most of the lighter people. The correlation is significantly stronger for females than for males. Possibly, and tragically, this is due to the higher pressure on females (compared to males) to meet cultural beauty standards. This relates to the team’s question because it shows that many people already have a good understanding of what weight they should be for optimal health, however, the distributions not very tight, so informing the public about these findings may still prove to be beneficial.
